photo.title: Ms. transcription of the Latin will of Sempronius Lucidanus in left-hand column with emended text in right-hand head column
photo.description: Ms. transcription of the Latin will of Sempronius Lucidanus (text also preserved in Biblioteca nazionale centrale di Firenze Ms. Palatino 270, cf. I Codici Palatini della R. Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze, v. 1, fasc. 1 (Rome: Presso i Principali Librai, 1885), p. 457) in left-hand column with emended text in right-hand head column. The transcriber apparently wishes to identify Sempronius Lucidanus as Sempronius Tuditanus (citing the career of P. Sempronius Tuditanus in the second Punic War in the note above the texts) and edits accordingly. Below the text appear to be brief notes on a legal issue it raises, with references to Justinian and Paul de Castro. Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-938 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Ms. transcription of two Latin verses associated with Olybius's lamp followed by the text of a letter purportedly written by the Italian humanist Francesco Maturanzio (d. 1518)
photo.description: Above: Venetijs repertum in arca latente : in qua vas futile clausum erat. Plutoni sacrum munus ne attingite fures. Ignotum est vobis hoc : quod in orbe latet. Nam[que] elementa graui clausit digesta labore Vase sub hoc modico maximus olybius. Adsit secundo custos sibi copia cornu : Ne pretium tanti depereat laticis. In eodem aliud uas fictile fuit inculsum cum his versibus. Abite hinc pessimi fures : Vos qui uoltis cum v[est]ris oculis emissitijs. Abite hinc cum v[est]ro mercurio petasato : caduceato[que] Maximus maximum donum plutoni hu[n]c sacrum facit. Metaratij viri consumatissimi ep[isto]la de re ista ad amicum. Nihil ex {corr. from: est} om[n]i anti[qui]tate uidisti mirabilius mi alphene: in uase illo interiori lucerna fuit fictilis mire pulcritudinis lumine tot seculis mextinato : Su[per] eam due ampulle parue : aurum in altera : in altera argentum fuit : vtrun[que] li[qui]dum. et ut ex ramentis cognoscitur : primarium Argentum : Aurum uero obryzum. Ego chimie artis : si modo uera potest esse ars chimia iurare possum elementa fuisse et materiam. Omnia : vas utru[m][que] cum epigra[m]matib[us] : lucerna : ampulle : aurum : olim in munere ad me uenere : et penes me sunt : que si videas : obstupeseas : et ego cum mille aureis no[n] sum co[m]mutaturus : vale. Da versus amicis rescribendos : et camerti pontifici : at[que] amico Gratiano in primis uetustatis studiossimis. [Ms. transcription of two Latin verses associated with Olybius's lamp, part of a classical burial putatively discovered still burning around the turn of the 16th century, followed by the text of a letter purportedly written by the Italian humanist Francesco Maturanzio (d. 1518) to a friend regarding this discovery. Cf. Corpus Inscriptionarum Latinarum V, pt. I, p. 22*, no. 194* (transcribed here).] Below: In Patrem cognomine Rubricam alios rigide obseruantem. Disticon. Ante Patres soliti semper seruare Rubricam, Nunc seruare Patres ipsa Rubrica solet. In Patrem cognomine Myrtum, Qui ut a Principe, q[uo]d cuperet obtineret, Amasiam in mediatricem elegit. Disticon. Marti grata Venus, Veneri gratissima Myrtus, Vt placeas Marti, Mirte, roga Venerem. [Two ms. Latin couplets in a later hand.] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-938 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Ms. inscriptions dated 1513 and 1515 recording the appearances in Rome and Geneva of a French boy with a conjoined twin
photo.description: Above: MDXIII Leonis X Pont. max. anno primo eidibus nouembr. Ex hispania fuit Romam aduectus puer natione Gallus annoru[m] xij Monstrum in pectore gerens ad forma[m] perfecti pueruli acephali brachijs tamen gracillimis sine manibus ostendentis caput suum intra pectus pueri condidisse et per paruum collum a pectore ip[s]ius dependere diuisis corporibus, ventribus inter se coherentibus genua pueri uix pedibus attingentis. Quodq[ue] mirum dictu est puer una cum monstro egerit, mingitq[ue], tamq[ue] cibo unius utriq[ue] alimenta prestentur. Et si quid monstrum tetigerit, puer statim sentit. H[a]ec non uulgaris fabula sed pleriq[ue] uiri fide digni cum Rom[a]e, tum in Hispania & Gallia hunc puerum mo[n]striferu[m] magnu[m] qu[a]estum facientem uiderunt. [Early ms. inscription recording the appearance in Rome in 1513 of a twelve-year-old French boy with a conjoined twin.] Beneath: 1 die veneris ija martij. 1515. Adolescens monstrifer nom[en] Jaquet Floquet postea peragratis pluribus Italie ciuitatibus questus causa genuam venit : ac hospitatus est in vicinia molis : et que de eo superius scripta sunt : hodie verissima fore deprehendi : duobus exceptis. nam monstrum ex stomaco : non ex pectore exit : nec egerit deficiente ano : mingit t[ame]n : et membrum virile habet. preterea non sunt plures dies : [que] monstrum h[abe]t tibias ita in poplitibus retractas : ut talis pedum suas nates attingat. cur ei ita acciderit : pleriq[ue] credunt : [qui]a monstrum adhuc crescens no[n] h[ab]ea[n]t solitum nutrime[n]tum : et ob hoc forte monstrifero breuiore[m] vita[m] portendit : ut et[iam] in aspectu de monstrat moestus et pallidus incedens : t[ame]n vultu modesto : et acco[m]modatis verbis : et quantum potui considerare circiter etatis anno[rum] xvj videtur. [Update in a different hand, dated 2 March 1515, on the anatomical peculiarities of the boy with the conjoined twin, here named Jaquet Floquet, whom the writer characterizes as gloomy and pale but also modest and well-spoken.] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-938 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Portion of leaf C4r (annotated and with early ms. sketch of a bird pecking at the eye of a man hanged on a gallows in left margin) from one of two editions of Sallust's Bellum Jugurthinum (Leipzig: Martin Landsberg, after 1500)
photo.description: Portion of leaf C4r (annotated and with early ms. sketch of a bird pecking at the eye of a man hanged on a gallows in left margin) from one of two editions of Sallust's Bellum Jugurthinum (Leipzig: Martin Landsberg, after 1500). In this edition (BSB-Ink. S-25; IBP 4859), line 1 of this leaf reads: "da fuga pleri[que] abiectis armis proximu[m] collem occupauere : nox at[que] preda". In another edition (GW M39666; VD 16 S 1397), this line reads: "seda fuga pleri[que] abiectis armis [pro]ximu[m] collem occupauere : nox at[que] p[re]da". (Goff S-88, giving an imprint consistent with the latter edition, appears to conflate the two.) Established heading: Sallust, 86-34 B.C. Established heading: Landsberg, Martin, d. 1523 Penn Libraries call number: Inc S-88 All images from this book

photo.title: Bookplate of James Carson Brevoort (1818-1887)
photo.description: Bookplate of James Carson Brevoort (1818-1887), American bibliophile, antiquarian and natural historian. He was a collector of rare books and coins. From his father, Henry Brevoort, he inherited about 6,000 volumes, mostly Americana, which were collected in Europe during the turbulent years from 1810 until 1832. To this library, Brevoort made large additions, until in 1875 it comprised about 10,000 volumes, many of them very rare and costly. He also collected medals and manuscripts. About 1875 he began to bestow many of his treasures upon various institutions. His collections also embraced entomology and ichthyology (books and specimens). Established heading: Brevoort, James Carson, 1818-1887 Penn Libraries call number: EC6 M6427 645pb All images from this book

photo.title: Metal-cut printer's device of Guy Marchant of Paris
photo.description: Metal-cut printer's device of Guy Marchant of Paris: "[T]he third of Guy Marchant's six devices ... At the top is a rebus consisting of musical notes, sol and la and the words Fides ficit, to represent the motto, 'Sola fides sufficit' (from the hymn, 'Pange lingua gloriosi,' of St. Thomas Aquinas). Below the motto are the initials, G and M, the G being set in type and the M cut in the block. Below these are two clasped hands issuing from clouds and flanked by angels. The device depicts the workshop of Saints Crispin and Crispinian, patron saints of shoemakers. It has been suggested that the presence of these saints might be explained if Marchant were a native of Soissons, where they were especially honored. Between the saints is a shield, with a book, possibly a Bible, held open by two hands. The word, sola (sole of the foot) and the boots in the shoeshop suggest the word marchant, a play on the printer's name." --M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 23. Established heading: Marchant, Guy Penn Libraries call number: Inc D-203 All images from this book

photo.title: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956)
photo.description: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established heading: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, 1887-1956 Other examples of Samuel Weiller Fernberger provenance Penn Libraries call number: EC6 F8484 630o
